I actually order from them all the time. Usually very great chicken and friendly people.  However it pains me to say— the Nashville Hot SHOULD NOT be on the menu. Or at least made into something realistically edible.  I got my usual, 3 piece meal and ordered my friend the spicy Nashville Hot. He LOVES spicy so I figured he’d enjoy it.  The chicken was incredibly too spicy. TEARS running down this grown persons’ face. Yes, they have a disclaimer—which is honestly a joke because they put “VERY Spicy” online. It should say, EAT AT YOUR OWN RISK HAVE WITH MILK”  Everything else is great but that Nashville hot. Trash. You literally can’t eat it as a serious meal, especially if you’re hungry.

This is one of my absolute favorite spots to eat in all of Boston/Cambridge. All of their food is delicious and packed with flavor. The Nashville Hot Wings are my favorite. It's not the spiciest sauce, but the overall balance is amazing. If you are not into spice, I would use some caution. (Elise - you were probably referencing me in your review. Like I said, I make my own hot sauces and I have an indestructible stomach. Use caution or ask for the Nashville hot on the side. Lots of folks react differently to spice)

We recently ordered the Nashville Hot Wings for takeout. There should be a warning or something on the menu. We love spicy food, but they were the spiciest wings we've ever eating. We could only eat 1 wing between the two of us. We've eaten wings before that have so many disclaimers on the menu, the servers tell us to be careful ordering, but they were not even close to as spicy as these wings. To save gory details, let's just say we definitely don't feel good. Another reviewer wrote that they aren't too spicy, so I wonder if they just made them extra spicy for us (we didn't ask for that). Two stars because their takeout procedure was very effective, easy to maintain social distancing, and the woman working at the front was very nice and kind. Never again. Do not order the Nashville Hot Wings unless you have a death wish.

Fried chicken 5/5 - extra crispy skin, juicy meat, all around would eat again and worth the money Mac and cheese 1/5 - undersalted, all around too “soft”. The elbow mac was cooked too long and just blended together with the cheese to eat like one soft texture. Wish they either cooked the pasta less time, picked a more assertive cheese flavor, added more salt, or picked a different type of pasta. We added some hot sauce which made it a little more flavorful but would not order this again Biscuit- 5/5 - very flaky and crispy. We had a side of chicken gravy for our fried chicken so dipped this in which was tasty. Probably also would’ve been good with honey butter Ribs - 5/5 - would order this again. All around tasty ribs Beef brisket- 3/5 - a little bit dry and underwhelming. We left 2 pieces because other parts of our meal were more worth the stomach room Potato salad- 4/5- all around good potato salad with pieces of carrots and other veggies to add a nice crunch. Would’ve possibly liked a pinch more salt Sausage- 2/5 - the 2 is for the nice snap that sausages should have. Otherwise we didn’t expect it to be SO spicy! I’m all for spicy but the spice wasn’t so balanced with sweetness or anything and the spice just gradually increased in my mouth to the point where I was coughing. I wasn’t sure how exactly the sausage tasted other than the spice. Would not order again Cornbread 1/5 - super dry and crumbly. Just not something I would order again  Would definitely come back here for the fried chicken, ribs, and biscuit. Other than that this place has should refine some of their menu options (mainly season their food better and add more balance to their flavors)

I was in the area running errands with my sister and Highland Fried appeared in my Google Maps feed as a restaurant I should try based on other restaurants I've visited. When we arrived they were busy but not packed. We were seated right away and browsed the most concise menu I've seen for a casual dining restaurant. With just the right amount of BBQ offerings and a recommendation from our waiter, Christian, I ordered the Barbecue Chopped Brisket Sandwich. This sandwich came topped with coleslaw and pickles and was served on a toasted buttered bun.  The pictures don't do this sandwich justice. Words won't do this sandwich justice!  It was Just. That. Good. Flavorful, moist, delicate, filling, fresh, complex...  I could go on and on and you could read on and on. Instead, do yourself a favor and pay them a visit so you, too, can be speechless. And satisfied. Very, very satisfied.

If you're looking for a total casual dining experience (food, drinks, service, atmosphere) Highland Fried is the place for you.  The staff was so friendly.  Our waiter, Christian, was knowledgeable and recommended we try the brisket sandwich. Upon speaking with Christan, we learned that all their meats are smoked in-house.  We asked to see the smoker and Christan asked chef/owner Mark Romano, who graciously obliged. It was a great experience to see how the food was prepared (did I mention the kitchen is visible from the dining room?), and an even better experience to meet such a talented chef.  When our food arrived, we weren't disappointed. The brisket sandwich was one of the best sandwiches I've ever had. My dining companion visited Texas recently, home of the brisket sandwich, and agreed: even if everything is bigger in Texas, it's definitely not better, as this sandwich proved!  I absolutely recommend you try them out. No matter where you're from, it's worth the trip, and I can't wait to dine again!

Highland Fried is a vibrant, millenio-hipster spot in Cambridge boasting basically the best fried chicken for miles. This is a colorful place to tuck in by the windows and enjoy one of their lovely cocktails, likely served in an appropriate glass with enough ice to cool the arctic and a lovely orchid or other equally elegant cocktail garnish. They are almost too beautiful to drink-- almost. The service is fine but don't expect the staff to bear the same southern disposition as the food; they retain the cooler, Cambridge aloofness that would be considered rude south of DC, but here is just totally normal. I was there for brunch and, though the menu is somewhat limited, the food was all well-prepared. Pancakes with fruit were voluminous. The blackened catfish was nicely spicy but a bit buried under eggs, so it lost any crunch. But above all was the fried chicken, which I had with biscuit and collards. The chicken was salty, crunchy, and just greasy enough so that you can be sure you are somewhere called _Highland Fried_. The collards were almost equal parts bbq pork & greens. I suppose there might have been an equivalent number of calories in the greens as the chicken. The biscuit was very typical, but rounded out the plate to help you reach the pinnacle of calories for the whole day in one plate. I walked back to my friend's place nearby as penance for that little plate of heaven. Check out highland fried- but bring your most hungry self because the name says it all.

I went in with a vague interest in trying some of their Nashville hot chicken, a style I'm familiar with but had never tried from any place that advertised itself as a serious chicken joint.  explained this to my lovely bartender, who was patient, friendly,  and thoughtful in guiding me away from a full order (which in retrospect would have gone to waste) and toward a "test" order of one drumstick.  This was some seriously hot chicken--moist and tender, very flavorful, with layers of heat that kept building from "oh, ok" to "yup, that's spicy!" to "I'm sorry, I stopped paying attention to what you were saying because I'm trying to manage this heat in my face." A side of perfect biscuits, a glass of beer, and the best pickleback I've had in a long time helped keep the spice from going from fun and exotic to a bad decision that won't go away.

I’m going to give this place a weak 4. I mean nothing was inherently bad ... but it also wasn’t amazing blow your mind great.  First the service was good - but to be somewhat expected on a non-busy Monday night.  The food. The deviled eggs were tasty. Coleslaw was light and spirited. Burnt ends were pretty good. albeit a little oily. The fried chicken sandwich was just OK - fried, a little greasy nothing to write home about but just ok-good. The two-patty burger was flavorful but quite greasy and wet, because of the grease + special sauce combo, and you have to manage it to eat it because of the grease and lack of friction ingredients to have it stay composed. Fries were good although could probably use a double-fry technique. Mac and cheese was lackluster, tasted like plain elbow macaroni because the cheese sauce ended at the bottom of the bowl. Fried chicken tasted more homemade - not a bad thing at all, but not the best fried chicken in the city.  That being said - overall a good experience. Try it if you want some chicken or BBQ and are in the area, but wouldn’t make a special trip.

On the heels of yesterday's take out from Highland Fried, I just had to go there in person to do a follow-up taste test.  And the verdict?  It's still incredibly flavorful deep fried chicken. I was curious about what they used to coat the chicken and I thought I tasted something in the coating that seemed to remind me of cereal.  It was a really light crunchy coating, taking a guess here, probably a mixture of seasoned flour, corn starch, some cereal and semolina. What I'm really thinking about is a deep satisfying crunch of a deep fried chicken skin. With the melt in your mouth, warm, juicy meat.  That's a tough one. The search for the world's best deep fried chicken continues.  P.s. I would take a pass on the collard greens and coleslaw.

The skin and batter was extra crispy and well seasoned. The meat was moist and steaming hot, as it is cooked to order. Be careful eating it because it is piping hot and the hot oil might drip on your fingers.  For the biscuit, it was a miss for me. It tasted like white bread with a biscuit texture. It was bland and I had to smother it with the honey butter that comes with it. Tip: ask for extra honey butter since you don't get much.  I had the coleslaw for the side and it was well worth it if you want something refreshing in between your chicken.  I would go here again for the chicken! Other than that, I recommend going on weekdays as you'll be waiting well over an hour on Friday and Saturday nights.
